tspan.tspan: Akin chemical risk assessment, microbial risk assessment shares the same basic framework and versatile
application to human health and ecological. Microbial risk assessments, however, remain notably limited by
available data on exposure parameters. In cases of synthetic biology (synbio) microorganisms, published data
often is non-existent or limited to the genome sequence only. Synbio organisms can pose a unique risk
through gaining unexpected functions and outcompeting local biota. Therefore, it is imperative to create a tool
that can estimate ecological risk based off an organism’s genome.
HazID is a component of a risk assessment tool, EcoGenoRisk, in development that identifies environments
susceptible to invasion and establishment by synbio organisms. The first phase of HazID consists of two parts:
NicheOverlap and CompetitorFind. NicheOverlap uses sequence aligner, DIAMOND, on a microbial sequence
library and complete microbial genomes with protein groups. Synbio organisms are annotated through the
same process and assigned a similarity score to all genomes through a functional presence-absence distance
metric. By comparing the new and uncharted organism to a protein-based library, uncertainty factors from lack
of genetic data through directly identification of protein functional groups. CompetitorFind employs databases
such as the Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) to determine the overall effect on metabolic
pathways when combining different functional proteins. The resulting similarity score from this phase of HazID
therefore combines functional and pathway similarity.
Further representing the often biomanufacturing nature of synbio organisms, HazID will be extended to

assess the effects of chemical by-products synthesized which can inhibit or promote biological processes of comparative biota. Further development of the EcoGenoRisk pipeline will produce a hazard identification list that is both environment and organism-specific. Overall, we foresee this as a comprehensive summary tool of multiple genomic databases to inform risk assessments during synbio product development and deployment.
